    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"oily water\" stage is a classic sign that the emulsion has fully given up the ghost, often because the butter melted too early or the yolk base was too cold to hold the fat together. You're likely over-whisking the yolk before the butter is incorporated, which creates too much friction and heat, or you're adding the cold butter too quickly. The ideal temperature for the yolk mixture is around 150°F (65°C), and the butter should be melted but not scalding (around 120°F/50°C) when you start adding it.\n\nSince the water trick didn't work, you'll need to start a completely fresh batch, but this time, use a double boiler to gently warm the yolk and lemon juice until it's just warm, not hot. Then, add the cold butter in tiny, slow increments while whisking vigorously in a circular motion. If you still get that oily look, it means the butter is still too cold or the yolk base isn't thick enough yet.\n\nThink of it like trying to herd a bunch of hyperactive goblins into a single line; if you rush it, they scatter. If you",
